very well. if you are on a strict budget, wait until the train stops at a station. there are normally vendors on the platform who sell noodles, snacks, and fruit at better prices. trains generally have boiled water available so bring tea, soups and instant noodles to make your own food. be careful with your valuables while on the train; property theft on public transportation has gone up in recent years. on most higher-level trains (t, k, z and crh trains) pre-recorded announcements are made in chinese, english and occasionally cantonese (if the train serves guangdong province or hong kong), 